'''Kataoka Shrine''' (かたおかじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} located in {{jalink|Yoshida Town|Q1202789}}, {{jalink|Haibara District|Q1203336}}, {{jalink|Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320}}. Its former {{jalink|shrine rank|Q10444029}} was that of a {{jalink|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines#Village shrines|Q712534|village shrine}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{jalink|Sumiyoshi Sanjin|Q1114013|Sokotsutsuo-no-Mikoto, Nakatsutsuo-no-Mikoto, Uwatsutsuo-no-Mikoto}}
* {{jalink|Empress Jingū|Q232803|Okinagatarashihime-no-Mikoto}}

=== Overview ===
According to shrine tradition, it is an ancient shrine that was invited from {{jalink|Yamato Province|Q907495}}’s {{jalink|Kataoka Shrine (Ōji, Nara)|Q43594918|Kataoka Shrine}}, and it is listed as a {{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|Shikinaisha}}.

During the reign of {{jalink|Emperor Nintoku|Q313119}}, a divided spirit was invited from {{jalink|Sumiyoshi Taisha|Q705949}} in {{jalink|Settsu Province|Q864163}}, after which it came to be known as Sumiyoshi Daimyōjin (Sumiyoshi Shrine). Following the {{jalink|Meiji Restoration|Q8707}}, Kataoka Shrine was adopted as the official shrine name.

Within the shrine grounds, the boat-shaped object “Sumiyoshi-maru” is displayed.

=== History ===
The date of foundation is unknown. Records indicate that the shrine buildings were rebuilt in the 4th year of {{jalink|Shōhō|Q1146192}} ({{jalink|1647|Q6935}}).

In {{jalink|1913|Q2080}} (the 2nd year of {{jalink|Taishō|Q329174}}), the shrine buildings were renovated from thatched roofing to tiled roofing, based on designs by {{jalink|Heisaemon Itō|Q16766564}}, an {{jalink|Imperial Household Artist|Q11481067}}.

After the war, the heiden (offering hall) was constructed<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese
  |author = Kataoka Shrine
  |url = http://homepage2.nifty.com/sugao/
  |title = Kataoka Shrine (History and Shrine Tradition)
  |accessdate = 2016-07-31 }}</ref>.

=== Auxiliary shrines ===
The auxiliary and related shrines within the precincts are as follows.

'''Shrines within the grounds'''
* Funatama Shrine
* Hoshinomiya Shrine
* Tsushima Shrine, Inari Shrine, Itsukushima Shrine
* Jūnishin Shrine, Nishinomiya Shrine, Kotohira Shrine

